thanks again.

--- In junit@yahoogroups.com, Timothy Wall &lt;twall@o...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Add another listener to your window for WINDOW_OPENED (note that 
this 
&gt; event is only posted once for any given window) which sets a flag.  
In 
&gt; your main test thread, wait for that flag to be set before posting 
the 
&gt; invokeAndWait empty runnable.  This ensures that your runnable gets 
&gt; processed *after* your original WINDOW_OPENED handler has finished 
&gt; (unless it spawns threads or some such).
&gt; 
&gt; You might also check out java-gui-testing@yahoogroups.com  There 
are 
&gt; several extensions to JUnit which are specifically designed to 
handle 
&gt; such issues (see the Links/Tools area of the group).
&gt; 
&gt; On Aug 22, 2004, at 2:45 AM, sagyrozman wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; &gt; thanks for the reply.
&gt; &gt; I was thinking the same thing but didn&#39;t know how to sync with the
&gt; &gt; AWT event queue thread.
&gt; &gt; I tried it and it passed at first attempt, but the next attempts
&gt; &gt; didn&#39;t always pass.
&gt; &gt; I think the problem is the empty runnable is sometimes added 
before
&gt; &gt; the setVisible(true) event is added to the queue, maybe because a
&gt; &gt; different thread (other than the main thread) is responsible for
&gt; &gt; adding the events to the AWT queue?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Is a there a different way to synchronize with the swing event 
queue?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; If this topic is out of scope for this discussion group, please 
let
&gt; &gt; me know. It might be better suited for a swing discussion group.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; --- In junit@yahoogroups.com, Timothy Wall &lt;twall@o...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;&gt; It&#39;s entirely possible that your main thread checks the mock 
status
&gt; &gt;&gt; prior to the events actually being handled.
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; Consider adding the following after frame.show():
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; SwingUtilities.invokeAndWait(new Runnable() { public void run()
&gt; &gt; { }});
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; On Aug 18, 2004, at 2:15 AM, sagyrozman wrote:
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; hi all,
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; I was writing a test for a GUI class which should delegate GUI
&gt; &gt; events
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; to another object:
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; class MyFrame extends JFrame implements WindowListener{
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; TargetForEvents target;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; public void setTarget(TargetForEvents t) {
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;    target = t;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; }
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; ....
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; }
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; in the test case:
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; ...
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; MyFrame frame = new MyFrame();
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; frame.setTarget(mockTarget);
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; frame.setVisible();
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; now I check that the expected functions where called on the 
taget
&gt; &gt; in
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; response to the WindowOpened events of MyFrame.
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; the test fails even though it should have passed because using 
the
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; eclipse debuger I can see that the mock is called upon in the
&gt; &gt; swing
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; event handling thread, but when checking back with the main 
thread
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; the mock is not affected by these changes.
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Another weird thing: I tried to do a similar test only not 
through
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; junit, instead of asserting that the methods where called, I 
wrote
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; the mock log string out to the stdout. This time the output 
shows
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; that all methods where called in the correct order.
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Am I missing something here? please let me know if any further
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; clarification is needed.
